Adjust racks to top and middle positions and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{9%ounce} on a diagonal into 1⁄2-inch-thick pieces. Dice @potatoes{12%ounce} into 1⁄2-inch pieces. Finely chop half the @?rosemary{1/4%ounce}(chopped) (all for 4 servings).

Toss carrots on one side of a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{4%teaspoon}, @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Toss potatoes on empty side of sheet with a large drizzle of oil, rosemary, a pinch of salt, and pepper.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pat @beef tenderloin filets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add beef and cook, turning occasionally, until browned all over, ~{4-8%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer beef to a second baking sheet. Wipe out pan.

Roast on middle rack until beef is cooked through, ~{10-12%minutes}. Transfer to a #cutting board{}.

> Swap in chicken or pork tenderloin for the beef. Cook chicken until browned and cooked through, 3-5 minutes per side, or cook pork to desired doneness, 4-7 minutes per side.

Meanwhile, roughly chop @parsley{1/4%ounce}(roughly chopped).

Once veggies and beef are done roasting, combine @cream sauce base{4%ounce}, @Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, 2 TBSP water (4 TBSP for 4 servings), and pepper in pan used for beef over medium-high heat.

Bring to a boil, then reduce to a simmer and cook, whisking constantly, until slightly reduced, ~{30-60%seconds}.

> If sauce is too thick, add water 1 tsp at a time until sauce reaches desired consistency.

Slice beef crosswise.

Divide beef, potatoes, and carrots between plates in separate sections. Spoon sauce over beef and potatoes and sprinkle with parsley. Serve.

> Slice chicken or pork against the grain.

> Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.